{Sometimes bidding is easy. Partner has 20 or 21 points, balanced. You have 13 points, balanced. Total = 33 or 34 points, balanced. So you close your eyes and bid 6NT.

The contract would be 6NT played by East.

To make West the declarer  ROTATE. 

West plays 6NT. North leads the \DT. Too bad North didn't lead a \S. Oh, well.

There is no way to get more than 4 winners in each minor suit, so you need to win either the \SJ or \HQ.

Which one should you try? 

Why not try both? If you make sure you try them in the right order you can have both chances. 

Suppose you lead a small \S from dummy and play your \SJ, and it loses to North's \SQ. If you then try leading a small \H toward dummy's \HQ, obviously the defender with the \HK will grab it to set the contract.

Instead, try the effect of leading toward the \HQ first. If North has the \HK then you will succeed in creating the extra winner you need. But what if you play the \HQ and South takes it with his \HK? Too bad, but at least you are not dead yet. You still have a chance to finesse  South for the \SQ.

There are two critical cards, the \SQ and the \HK. However they are not the same degree of criticality.

If the \SQ is in a favorable position, (with South), you are always going to make your contract no matter which you try first.

But if only the \HK is in a favorable position, (with North), you can make the contract only if you try \Hs first.}
